722358f-a.text:
1022-1024 Park Avenue, west side, between 85th and 86th Streets, showing doorway of the Stattinius house on the 85th Street corner, No. 1020, and part of 1026.
The two brownstones, 1022-24, have been sold, and will later be replaced by more modern residences almost the same size, No. 1022 by the residence of Mrs. Reginald De Koven. Compare Sperr's picture of this block in 1928.

Early 1912.

722357f-a.text:
Park Avenue, north on west side, from 85th to 86th Streets. The house on the N. W. corner of 85th Street is the residence of the late Edward R. Stettinius, and the one above it belongs to Mrs.
Reginald De Koven.
The block still stands in 1935, althoumh the Stettinius house was bought by a builder in August 1928 with the idea of demolishing it.
February 30, 1928 [sic]
P.L. Sperr,Photographer.
Neg #824:

722356f-a.text:
Park Avenue, at S.W. corner of 85th Street, showing the Park Avenue Presbyterian Church and Rectory (built in 1909).
September 25, 1932.
P.L. Sperr, Photographer.

714681f-a.text:
112 to 118 East 85th Street (right to left), adjoining and east of the S.E. corner of Park Ave. No. 112 is occupied by the Kewahnew and the Micanopee Democratic Clubs. The two adjoining structures, Nos. 114 and 116 are the quarters of the New York College of Music.
August 13, 1937.
Gift of Geo. D. Chinn.

714682f-a.text:
108-110 East 85th Street, south side, east of Park Avenue. These buildings will soon be demolished to make way for an apartment house.
About 1912.
